More than 2,000 agents from the NCIC, NIS and civil society groups will be deployed in the Rift Valley to monitor political party primaries next week.The move comes amid reports that some aspirants may use tribalism to sway support during the primaries in areas considered hotspots and are inhabited by many communities.Police have also beefed up security in areas where incidents of violence may occur.&ldquo;What we will not tolerate are any forms of violence, threats, intimidation, hate speech or utterances that may threaten unity and stability,&rdquo; Uasin Gishu county commissioner Abdi Hassan said yesterday.Incidents of violence have been reported in parts of the county, and aspirants had been cautioned to be civilised manner.